In mathematics, a '''fusion category''' is a [[category (mathematics)|category]] that is [[rigid category|rigid]], [[semisimple category|semisimple]], [[linear category|<math>k</math>-linear]], [[monoidal category|monoidal]] and has only finitely many isomorphism classes of [[Glossary_of_category_theory#simple_object|simple objects]], such that the monoidal unit is simple. If the ground field <math>k</math> is algebraically closed, then the latter is equivalent to <math>\mathrm{Hom}(1,1)\cong k</math> by [[Schur's lemma]].
==Examples==

* [[Representation_theory_of_finite_groups|Representation Category of a finite group]]

==Reconstruction==

Under [[Tannaka-Krein duality]], every fusion category arises as the representations of a [[weak Hopf algebra]].

